These implicits are pretty opaque. All they are really doing are allowing you to convert a Dataset to a Dataframe by .toDF(), everything else is the same. It would be cleaner to have an implicit which just does the cast ie 

```
implicit class DatasetToDf[T1](ds: Dataset[T1]) {

    def df(
    ): Dataframe =
      ds.toDF()
  }
```

and then one instance of the writeToParquet function which takes a Dataframe as a param (or a separate implicit class for writing if you really want). Generally though implicits only make sense if you are re-using them a lot, and it seems like you only call this write function twice? Probably much easier to read and understand if you do the toDF() call manually unless you expect to be using this a lot more?

Okay so I looked into it, and it is possible that the serviceName could be `elasticsearch-service` for a 32-bit machine, so I have added a check for the processor architecture, which sets the serviceName accordingly i.e:

```bash
